<section xml:id="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-using-a-square-root">

    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Using a Square Root</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equations-using-square-root-property" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equation-applications" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-factoring">Section</xref>, we learned how to solve quadratic equations by factoring. In this section, we will learn how to solve some specific types of quadratic equations using the <term>square root property</term>. We will also learn how to use the <term>Pythagorean Theorem</term> to find the length of one side of a right triangle when the other two lengths are known.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtubelist="PLmuZCPhWPt-fBul1o0Y4RxNEI5C1mE2lz"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Quadratic Equations Using the Square Root Property</title><idx><h>solving</h><h>quadratic equations</h><h>using the square root property</h></idx>

        <p>When we learned how to solve linear equations, we used inverse operations to isolate the variable. For example, we use subtraction to remove an unwanted term that is added to one side of a linear equation. We can't quite do the same thing with squaring and using square roots, but we can do something very similar. Taking the square root is the inverse of squaring <em>if you happen to know the original number was positive</em>. In general, we have to remember that the original number may have been negative, and that usually leads to <em>two</em> solutions to a quadratic equation.</p>

        <p>For example, if <m>x^2=9</m>, we can think of undoing the square with a square root, and <m>\sqrt{9}=3</m>. However, there are <em>two</em> numbers that we can square to get <m>9</m>: <m>-3</m> and <m>3</m>. So we need to include both solutions. This brings us to the Square Root Property.</p>

        <fact xml:id="fact-square-root-property">
            <title>The Square Root Property</title>
            <idx><h>square root property</h></idx><idx><h>properties</h><h>square root property</h></idx>
            <statement>
                <p>If <m>k</m> is positive, and <m>x^2=k</m> then <m>x=-\sqrt{k}</m> or <m>x=\sqrt{k}</m>. The positive solution, <m>\sqrt{k}</m>, is called the <term>principal root</term> of <m>k</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </fact>

        <example xml:id="example-solve-using-square-root-property">
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>y</m> in <m>y^2-49=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>While we could factor and use the <xref ref="fact-zero-product-property" text="title" />, here we are demonstrating <xref ref="fact-square-root-property" text="title" /> instead. Before we use the square root property, we need to isolate the squared quantity.<md>
                    <mrow>y^2-49\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y^2-49\addright{49}\amp=0\addright{49}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y^2\amp=49</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\sqrt{49} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp y\amp=\sqrt{49}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-7\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp y\amp=7</mrow>
                </md></p>
                <p>To check these solutions, we will replace <m>y</m> with <m>-7</m> and with <m>7</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>y^2-49\amp=0\amp y^2-49\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(\substitute{-7})^2-49\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp (\substitute{7})^2-49\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
                    <mrow>49-49\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp 49-49\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0\amp 0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-7,7\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <remark>
            <p>Every solution to a quadratic equation can be checked, as shown in <xref ref="example-solve-using-square-root-property">Example</xref>. In general, the process of checking is omitted from this section.</p>
        </remark>

        <remark>
            <p>Factoring will generally be a possible approach to solving a quadratic equation when the solution(s) are rational, but won't be a possible approach when the solution(s) are irrational.</p>

            <p>For example, we could have solved the quadratic equation in <xref ref="example-solve-using-square-root-property">Example</xref> by factoring in this way:<md>
                <mrow>y^2-49\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(y+7)(y-7)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>y+7\amp=0\amp\amp\text{ or }\amp y-7\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>y\amp=-7\amp\amp\text{ or }\amp y\amp=7</mrow>
            </md></p>
            <p>However, as we'll see in <xref ref="example-solve-using-square-root-property-irrational-cannot-factor">Example</xref>, we <em>cannot</em> solve <m>2n^2-3=0</m> by factoring but we <em>can</em> use the square root property.</p>
        </remark>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context("LimitedRadical");
                        Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0,
                            reduceConstantFunctions=>0,
                            formatStudentAnswer=>parsed,
                            showExtraParens=>0);
                        parser::Assignment->Allow;
                        Context()->operators->redefine(',',using=>',',from=>'Numeric');
                        Context()->operators->redefine('or',using=>',',from=>'Numeric');
                        Context()->operators->set(
                            ','=>{string=>' or ', TeX=>'\hbox{ or }'},
                            'or'=>{string=>' or ', TeX=>'\hbox{ or }'}
                        );
                        Context()->lists->set(List => {separator => 'or'});
                        Context()->strings->add("no real solutions"=>{},
                            "no real solution"=>{alias=>'no real solutions'},
                            "none"=>{alias=>'no real solutions'},
                        );
                        Context()->variables->are(z=>'Real');
                        $answer = List(Formula("z=-9/2"),Formula("z=9/2"));
                        $evaluator=$answer->cmp(list_checker => ~~&amp;radicalListCheck);
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>Solve for <m>z</m> in <m>4z^2-81=0</m>.</p>
                    <instruction>Enter multiple answers in the form <c>z=1 or z=-1</c>. If you need to use the square root symbol, as in <m>\sqrt{17}</m>, type it as <c>sqrt(17)</c>.</instruction>
                    <p><var name="$answer" evaluator="$evaluator" width="20" /></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Before we use the square root property we need to isolate the squared quantity.<md>
                        <mrow>4z^2-81\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>4z^2\amp=81</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{4z^2}{4}\amp=\divideunder{81}{4}</mrow>
                        <mrow>z^2\amp=\frac{81}{4}</mrow></md><md>
                        <mrow>z\amp=-\sqrt{\frac{81}{4}} \amp\text{ or }\amp\amp z\amp=\sqrt{\frac{81}{4}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>z\amp=-\frac{9}{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp z\amp=\frac{9}{2}</mrow>
                    </md>The solution set is <m>\left\{-\frac{9}{2},\frac{9}{2}\right\}</m>. </p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>

        <p>We can also use the square root property to solve an equation that has a squared expression. </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>p</m> in <m>50=2(p-1)^2</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>It's important here to suppress any urge you may have to expand the squared binomial. We begin by isolating the squared expression.<md>
                    <mrow>50\amp=2(p-1)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{50}{2}\amp=\divideunder{2(p-1)^2}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>25\amp=(p-1)^2</mrow>
                    <intertext>Now that we have the squared expression isolated, we can use the square root property.</intertext>
                    <mrow>(p-1)\amp=-\sqrt{25}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp(p-1)\amp=\sqrt{25}</mrow>
                    <mrow>p-1\amp=-5\amp\text{or}\amp\amp p-1\amp=5</mrow>
                    <mrow>p-1\addright{1}\amp=-5\addright{1}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp p-1\addright{1}\amp=5\addright{1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>p\amp=-4\amp\text{or}\amp\amp p\amp=6</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\{-4,6\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>This method of solving quadratic equations is not limited to equations that have rational solutions, or when the radicands are perfect squares. We'll now look at a few examples where the solutions are irrational numbers.</p>

        <exercise>
            <webwork>
                <setup>
                    <pg-code>
                        Context("LimitedRadical");
                        Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0,
                            reduceConstantFunctions=>0,
                            formatStudentAnswer=>parsed,
                            showExtraParens=>0);
                        parser::Assignment->Allow;
                        Context()->operators->redefine(',',using=>',',from=>'Numeric');
                        Context()->operators->redefine('or',using=>',',from=>'Numeric');
                        Context()->operators->set(
                            ','=>{string=>' or ', TeX=>'\hbox{ or }'},
                            'or'=>{string=>' or ', TeX=>'\hbox{ or }'}
                        );
                        Context()->lists->set(List => {separator => 'or'});
                        Context()->strings->add("no real solutions"=>{},
                            "no real solution"=>{alias=>'no real solutions'},
                            "none"=>{alias=>'no real solutions'},
                        );
                        Context()->variables->are(q=>'Real');
                        $answer = List(Formula("q=-2sqrt(3)-2"),Formula("q=2sqrt(3)-2"));
                        $evaluator=$answer->cmp(list_checker => ~~&amp;radicalListCheck);
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>Solve for <m>q</m> in <m>(q+2)^2-12=0</m>.</p>
                    <instruction>Enter multiple answers in the form <c>q=1 or q=-1</c>. If you need to use the square root symbol, as in <m>\sqrt{17}</m>, type it as <c>sqrt(17)</c>.</instruction>
                    <p><var name="$answer" evaluator="$evaluator" width="20" /></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>It's important here to suppress any urge you may have to expand the squared binomial.<md>
                        <mrow>(q+2)^2-12\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>(q+2)^2\amp=12</mrow></md><md>
                        <mrow>(q+2)\amp=-\sqrt{12}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp(q+2)\amp=\sqrt{12}</mrow>
                        <mrow>q+2\amp=-2\sqrt{3}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp q+2\amp=2\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>q+2\subtractright{2}\amp=-2\sqrt{3}\subtractright{2}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp q+2\subtractright{2}\amp=2\sqrt{3}\subtractright{2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>q\amp=-2\sqrt{3}-2\amp\text{or}\amp\amp q\amp=2\sqrt{3}-2</mrow>
                    </md>The solution set is <m>\{-2\sqrt{3}-2,2\sqrt{3}-2\}</m>.</p>

                    <p>To check the solution, we would replace <m>q</m> with each of <m>-2\sqrt{3}-2</m> and <m>2\sqrt{3}-2</m> in the original equation, as shown here:<md>
                        <mrow>((\substitute{-2\sqrt{3}-2})+2)^2-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp((\substitute{2\sqrt{3}-2})+2)^2-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
                        <mrow>(-2\sqrt{3})^2-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp (2\sqrt{3})^2-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
                        <mrow>(-2)^2(\sqrt{3})^2-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp (2)^2(\sqrt{3})^2-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
                        <mrow>(4)(3)-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp (4)(3)-12\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
                        <mrow>12-12\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0\amp\amp\amp 12-12\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0</mrow>
                    </md>Note that these simplifications relied on exponent rules and the multiplicative property of square roots.</p>
                </solution>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>

        <p>Remember that if a square root is in the denominator then we need to rationalize it like we learned in <xref ref="section-square-root-properties">Section</xref>. We will need to rationalize the denominator in the next example.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-solve-using-square-root-property-irrational-cannot-factor">
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>n</m> in <m>2n^2-3=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>2n^2-3\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>2n^2\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>n^2\amp=\frac{3}{2}</mrow></md><md>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}\amp\text{or}\amp\amp n\amp=\sqrt{\frac{3}{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{2}} \amp\text{or}\amp\amp n\amp=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\frac{\sqrt{3}\cdot\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}} \amp\text{or}\amp\amp n\amp=\frac{\sqrt{3}\cdot\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{2}\cdot\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>n\amp=-\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2}\amp\text{ or }\amp\amp n\amp=\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2}</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>\left\{-\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2},\frac{\sqrt{6}}{2}\right\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>When the radicand is a negative number, there is no real solution. Here is an example of an equation with no real solution.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>x</m> in <m>x^2+49=0</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>x^2+49\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2\amp=-49</mrow>
                </md>Since <m>\sqrt{-49}</m> is not a real number, we say the equation has no real solution.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="subsection-pythagorean-theorem">
        <title>The Pythagorean Theorem</title>
        <p>Right triangles have an important property called the <term>Pythagorean Theorem</term>.</p>

        <theorem xml:id="theorem-pythagorean-theorem">
            <title>The Pythagorean Theorem</title><idx><h>Pythagorean theorem</h></idx>
            <p>For any right triangle, the lengths of the three sides have the following relationship: <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m>. The sides <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are called <term>legs</term> and the longest side <m>c</m> is called the <term>hypotenuse</term>.</p>

            <figure>
                <caption>In a right triangle, the length of its three sides satisfy the equation <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m></caption>
                <image width="35%">
                    <description>a right triangle with sides labeled a, b, and c; side c is the hypotenuse</description>
                    <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm]
                            \draw (0,0) -- node[pos=0.5,below]{$a$} (3,0) --node[pos=0.5,right]{$b$} (3,4) --node[pos=0.5,above,sloped]{$c$} cycle;
                            \draw (3,0.2) -- (2.8,0.2) -- (2.8,0);
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </theorem>

        <example>
            <sidebyside widths="59% 35%" margins="0%">
                <p>Keisha is designing a wooden frame in the shape of a right triangle, as shown in <xref ref="figure-wooden-frame">Figure</xref>. The legs of the triangle are <quantity><mag>3</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> and <quantity><mag>4</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity>. How long should she make the diagonal side? Use the Pythagorean Theorem to find the length of the hypotenuse.</p>

                <figure xml:id="figure-wooden-frame">
                    <caption>Wooden Frame</caption>
                    <image width="35%">
                        <description>a right triangle with a base labeled a=3 ft; the height is labeled b=4 ft; the hypotenuse is labeled c</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (0,0) node[below left]{$B$} -- node[pos=0.5,below]{$a=3\,\text{ft}$}
                                   (3,0) node[below right]{$C$} -- node[pos=0.5,right]{$b=4\,\text{ft}$}
                                   (3,4) node[above right]{$A$} -- node[pos=0.5,above,sloped]{$c$}
                                   cycle;
                                \draw (3,0.2) -- (2.8,0.2) -- (2.8,0);
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>

            <p>According to Pythagorean Theorem, we have:<md>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=a^2+b^2</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=3^2+4^2</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=9+16</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2\amp=25</mrow>
                <intertext>Now we have a quadratic equation that we need to solve. We need to find the number that has a square of <m>25</m>. That is what the square root operation does.</intertext>
                <mrow>c\amp=\sqrt{25}</mrow>
                <mrow>c\amp=5</mrow>
            </md>The diagonal side Keisha will cut is <quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> long.</p>

            <p>Note that <m>-5</m> is also a solution of <m>c^2=25</m> because <m>(-5)^2=25</m> but a length cannot be a negative number. We will need to include both solutions when they are relevant.</p>
        </example>

        <example>
            <p>A <m>16.5</m>ft ladder is leaning against a wall. The distance from the base of the ladder to the wall is <m>4.5</m> feet. How high on the wall can the ladder reach?</p>

            <sidebyside widths="59% 35%" margins="0%">
                <p>The Pythagorean Theorem says:<md>
                    <mrow>a^2+b^2\amp=c^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>4.5^2+b^2\amp=16.5^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>20.25+b^2\amp=272.25</mrow>
                    <intertext>Now we need to isolate <m>b^2</m> in order to solve for <m>b</m>:</intertext>
                    <mrow>20.25+b^2\subtractright{20.25}\amp=272.25\subtractright{20.25}</mrow>
                    <mrow>b^2\amp=252</mrow>
                    <intertext>To remove the square, we use the square root property. Because this is a geometric situation we only need to use the principal root:</intertext>
                    <mrow>b\amp=\sqrt{252}</mrow>
                    <intertext>Now simplify this radical and then approximate it:</intertext>
                    <mrow>b\amp=\sqrt{36\cdot 7}</mrow>
                    <mrow>b\amp=6\sqrt{7}</mrow>
                    <mrow>b\amp\approx 15.87</mrow>
                </md></p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Leaning Ladder</caption>
                    <image width="35%">
                        <description>a right angle with a diagonal line for the ladder; the base of the triangle is labeled a=4.5 ft;the height of the triangle is labeled b; the hypotenuse is labeled c=16.5 ft</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm]
                                \draw (-9,0) -- (-4.5,0) --node[pos=0.5,below]{$a=4.5\,\text{ft}$} (0,0) --node[pos=0.5,right]{$b$}  (0,15.9) -- (0,20);
                                \draw[ultra thick] (-4.5,0) --node[sloped,pos=0.5,above]{$c=16.5\,\text{ft}$} (0,15.9);
                                \draw (-0.6,0) -- (-0.6,0.6) -- (0,0.6);
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </sidebyside>
            <p>The ladder can reach about <m>15.87</m> feet high on the wall.</p>
        </example>

        <p>Here are some more examples using the Pythagorean Theorem to find sides of triangles. Note that in many contexts, only the principal root will be relevant.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the missing length in this right triangle.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>A Right Triangle</caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                        <description>a right triangle with a base of 5 units and a hypotenuse of 10 units;the height is labeled x</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm]
                                \draw (-5,0) --node[pos=0.5,below]{$5$} (0,0) --node[pos=0.5,right]{$x$} (0,8.7) --node[pos=0.5,sloped,above]{$10$} cycle;
                                \draw (-0.4,0) -- (-0.4,0.4) -- (0,0.4);
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will use the Pythagorean Theorem to solve for <m>x</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>5^2+x^2\amp=10^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>25+x^2\amp=100</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2\amp=75</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{75}\amp\text{no need to consider }-\sqrt{75}\text{ in this context}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{25\cdot3}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=5\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                </md>The missing length is <m>x=5\sqrt{3}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Sergio is designing a <m>50</m>-inch TV, which implies the diagonal of the TV's screen will be <m>50</m> inches long. He needs the screen's width to height ratio to be <m>4:3</m>. Find the TV screen's width and height.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Pythagorean Theorem Problem</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description>a rectangle for the TV with a diagonal line drawn and labeled c=50 in; the base width of the TV is labeled a and the height is labeled b</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm]
                                \draw (0,0) rectangle (4,3);
                                \draw (0,0) -- (4,3);
                                \draw [below] (2,0) node {$a$};
                                \draw [right] (4,1.5) node {$b$};
                                \draw (2,1.5) node [above, rotate=36.9]{$c=50$in};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>Let's let <m>x</m> represent the height of the screen, in inches. Since the screen's width to height ratio will be <m>4:3</m>, then the width is <m>\frac{4}{3}</m> times as long as the height, or <m>\frac{4}{3}x</m> inches. We will draw a diagram.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Pythagorean Theorem Problem</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <description>The previous image of the TV with the height labeled b=x in and the base width labeled a=4/3x in</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm,y=0.5cm]
                                \draw (0,0) rectangle (4,3);
                                \draw (0,0) -- (4,3);
                                \draw [below] (2,0) node {$a=\frac{4}{3}x$ in};
                                \draw [right] (4,1.5) node {$b=x$ in};
                                \draw (2,1.5) node [above, rotate=36.9]{$c=50$ in};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Now we can use the Pythagorean Theorem to write and solve an equation:<md>
                    <mrow>a^2+b^2\amp=c^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\left(\frac{4}{3}x\right)^2+(x)^2\amp=50^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{16}{9}x^2+x^2\amp=2500</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{16}{9}x^2+\frac{9}{9}x^2\amp=2500</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{25}{9}x^2\amp=2500</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{9}\frac{25}{9}x^2\amp=2500\multiplyright{9}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{25x^2}{25}\amp=\divideunder{22500}{25}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2\amp=900</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=\sqrt{900}</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=30</mrow>
                </md>Since the screen's height is <m>30</m> inches, its width is <m>\frac{4}{3}x=\frac{4}{3}(30)=40</m> inches.</p>
            </solution>

