        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Luca wanted to make a bench.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Sketch of a Bench with Highlighted Back</caption>
                    <!-- TODO: make the bench wider or the backrest shorter so that the backrest could be 48x3 inches. I was having trouble visualizing the next images because the proportion is different  -->
                    <image width="47%">
                        <description>a sketch of a bench with an arc drawn on the backrest of the bench</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[axis x line=none, axis y line=none, xmin=-0.5,xmax=4.5,ymin=-0.5,ymax=3.5]
                                \addplot[color=black, very thick] coordinates{(0,0)(0,2)(1,2.5)(1,1.5)(0,1)(3,1)(3,0)(3,1)(3,2)(4,2.5)(4,0.5)(4,1.5)(3,1)(4,1.5)(4,3)(1,3)(1,1.5)(3,1.5)};
                                \addplot[color=blue, very thick,fill=gray!60!white] coordinates{(1,2.5)(1,3)(4,3)(4,2.5)(1,2.5)};
                                \addplot[color=black, dotted, very thick] coordinates{(3,1.5)(4,1.5)};
                                \addplot[color=black, dotted, very thick] coordinates{(1,1.5)(1,1)};
                                \addplot[color=black, very thick] coordinates{(1,0.5)(1,1)};
                                \addplot[variable=\t, domain=53.13:126.87, samples=100, dashed, thick, color=firstcolor]({2.5*cos(t)+2.5}, {2.5*sin(t)+0.5});
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">

                    <p>He wanted the top of the bench back to be a perfect portion of a circle, in the shape of an arc, as in <xref ref="figure-bench-back-board">Figure</xref>. (Note that this won't be a half-circle, just a small portion of a circular edge.) He started with a rectangular board <m>3</m> inches wide and <m>48</m> inches long, and a piece of string, like a compass, to draw a circular arc on the board. How long should the string be so that it can be swung round to draw the arc?</p>

                    <figure xml:id="figure-bench-back-board">
                        <caption>Bench Back Board</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>the bench backrest board labeled 48 in by 3 in and a large circle that makes the arc on the board;there is a dot in the center of the circle</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[axis x line=none, axis y line=none, xmin=-100, xmax=105, ymin=-100, ymax=100, axis equal]
                                    \addplot[color=black, fill=gray!60!white] coordinates{(88.92,-40)(97.5,-40)(97.5,40)(88.92,40)(88.92,-40)} node [left, pos=0.75]{$48\,\text{in}$} node [above, pos=.53]{$3\,\text{in}$};
                                    \addplot[color=black, only marks] coordinates{(0,0)} node [below]{circle center};
                                    \addplot[variable=\t, domain=0:360, samples=100, dashed, thin, color=blue] ({97.5*cos(t)}, {97.5*sin(t)});
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Let's first define <m>x</m> to be the radius of the circle in question, in inches. The circle should go through the bottom corners of the board and just barely touch the top of the board. That means that the line from the middle of the bottom of the board to the center of the circle will be <m>3</m> inches shorter than the radius.</p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Bench Back Board Diagram</caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                        <description>a diagram using the radii of the circle to form a triangle with the bench back board; The base of the triangle is a radius that is horizontal from the center of the circle to the bottom of the backrest, labeled x-3; The hypotenuse is another radius from the center of the circle to the corner of the backrest, labeled x; the height of the triangle is labeled 24 in from the center to edge of the backrest   </description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[axis x line=none, axis y line=none, xmin=-10, xmax=100, ymin=-50, ymax=50,width=0.6*\textwidth]
                                \addplot[color=black, fill=gray!60!white] coordinates{(88.92,-40)(97.5,-40)(97.5,40)(88.92,40)(88.92,-40)};
                                \addplot[color=blue, dashed,<->] coordinates{(88.92,-40)(0,0)};
                                \addplot[color=orange!70!black, thick, dashed,<->] coordinates{(0,0)(88.92,40)} node [below, pos=0.5, rotate=24.22,color=black]{$x$};
                                \addplot[color=blue!70!black, thick, dashed,<->] coordinates{(0,0)(88.92,0)} node [above, pos=0.6]{$x-3$};
                                \addplot[color=red!60!black, thick, dashed,<->] coordinates{(88.92,40)(88.92,0)} node [left, pos=0.5]{$24\,\text{in}$};
                                \addplot[color=green!40!black, dashed,<->] coordinates{(97.5,0)(88.92,0)} node [above, pos=0.5]{$3\,\text{in}$};
                                \addplot[color=black, only marks] coordinates{(0,0)(88.92,0)} node[pos=0, above]{center};
                                \addplot[variable=\t, domain=0:360, samples=100, dashed, thin, color=blue]({97.5*cos(t)}, {97.5*sin(t)});
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
                <p>Now we can set up the Pythagorean Theorem based on the scenario. The equation <m>a^2+b^2=c^2</m> turns into<ellipsis/><md>
                    <mrow>(x-3)^2+24^2\amp=x^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2-6x+9+576\amp=x^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>-6x+585\amp=0</mrow>
                    <intertext>Note that at this point the equation is no longer quadratic! Solve the linear equation by isolating <m>x</m></intertext>
                    <mrow>6x\amp=585</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=97.5</mrow>
                </md>So, the circle radius required is <m>97.5</m> inches. Luca found a friend to stand on the string end and drew a circular segment on the board to great effect.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
