                    <statement>
                        <p>Imagine that you are in Math Land, where roads are perfectly straight, and Mathlanders can walk along a perfectly straight line between any 2 points.</p>
                        <p>One day, you bike <var name="$west" /> miles west, <var name="$north" /> miles north, and <var name="$east" /> miles east.  Then, your bike gets a flat tire and you have to walk home.  How far do you have to walk?</p>
                        <p>I have to walk <var name="$answer" width="10"/>miles home.</p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
                        <p>You biked <var name="$west" /> miles west, <var name="$north" /> miles north, and <var name="$east" /> miles east.  You are <var name="$north" /> miles north and <var name="$factor" /> miles east of your home.  These are two sides of a right triangle.  Thus, you must use the Pythagorean Theorem to find out how far you walked home. </p>
                        <p> Solve this equation for <m>c</m>: </p>
                        <p><m> <var name="$north" />^{2} + <var name="$factor" />^{2} = c^{2}</m>.</p>
